# Unified environment variables

Keep one canonical environment file for committed defaults and examples: `.env.local.example`.

## Requirements

- Add new environment variables only in `.env.local.example`.
- Do not introduce additional committed env files for the same purpose (for example `.env.example`, `.env.dev.example`, or duplicated per-service examples) unless the task explicitly requires and documents an exception.
- Keep the variable list short and unified. Reuse existing keys before adding new ones.
- If a variable is removed or renamed, update all code/docs references in the same task.

## Examples

```bash
# BAD: defining new keys in a second example file
# .env.example
NEW_API_URL=...
```

```bash
# GOOD: keep the key in the canonical file
# .env.local.example
NEW_API_URL=...
```
